Question 1:

Define supervised and unsupervised learning. What are the difference(s) between them? - In Supervised learning: (from lecture 1 slides) Prediction: accurately predict future response given predictors Estimation: understand how predictors affect response Model selection: find the best model for response given predictors Inference: assess the quality of our predictions and (or) estimation

  • In unsupervised learning,the outcome is unknown and where unlabeled data is used to discover hidden patterns in data without the need for human intervention (hence, they are unsupervised).

  • Supervised learning is the outcome is known vs.unsupervised learning is when the outcome is unknown

Question 2:

Explain the difference between a regression model and a classification model, specifically in the context of machine learning.

Machine Learning problems can be characterized into regression or classification models.

  • In a regression model, Y is quantitative (or continuous) such as price, blood, pressure (lecture2 slide1)
  • In a classification model Y is qualitative (categorical)(e.g., survived/died, spam/not spam) (lecture2 slide1)

Two commonly used metrics for classification ML problems

Question 5:

Predictive models are frequently used in machine learning, and they can usually be described as either mechanistic or empirically-driven. Answer the following questions.

Define mechanistic. Define empirically-driven. How do these model types differ? How are they similar?

  • Empirically-driven (or non-parametric) model relies on observations (i.e.no assumptions about f), requires a larger # of observations, is much more flexible and could run into overfitting. (lecture 2 slide 6)

  • A mechanistic model (parametric) uses a theory to predict what will happen in the real world (assume a parametric form for f). The model wont match true unknown f, adding more parameters allows for more flexibility.However, too many parameters could result in overfitting.

  • A mechanistic model uses theory to predict what will happen in the real world. On the other hand, empirical modeling, studies real-world events (i.e.observations) to develop a theory.

  • Both models run into overfitting issues whether its by adding too many parameters (mechanistic) or by using too many observation (empirical)

In general, is a mechanistic or empirically-driven model easier to understand? Explain your choice.

Mechanistic model assumes a parametric form for f and therefore its easier to work with. However, its all depends on the available data were working with. In some situations, mechanistic models could be easier to use but in models where observations are available its would be easier to use an empirical model and sometimes both models could be needed to help with understanding the outcome.(lecture2 slides)

Describe how the bias-variance tradeoff is related to the use of mechanistic or empirically-driven models.

The bias tradeoff of mechanistic or empirically-driven models come with the use of extra parameters that lead to over fitting or using too many observations to over fit the data. This will likely bias the outcome of the models and remove any variance from the models making the models too good to be true.

A political candidates campaign has collected some detailed voter history data from their constituents. The campaign is interested in two questions:

Given a voters profile/data, how likely is it that they will vote in favor of the candidate?

The observations from the voters profile/data can help us understand their political inclination and help with predicting their voting outcome.

How would a voters likelihood of support for the candidate change if they had personal contact with the candidate?

If they had a personal contact with the candidate the voters likelihood of support will increase significantly

Classify each question as either predictive or inferential. Explain your reasoning for each.

Te first question uses observations from the voters profile data to predict their voting outcome. The second question infers that since the candidate has a relationship with the candidate they will likely vote for him

Exploratory Data Analysis

This section will ask you to complete several exercises. For this homework assignment, well be working with the mpg data set that is loaded when you load the tidyverse. Make sure you load the tidyverse and any other packages you need.

Exploratory data analysis (or EDA) is not based on a specific set of rules or formulas. It is more of a state of curiosity about data. Its an iterative process of: generating questions about data visualize and transform your data as necessary to get answers use what you learned to generate more questions A couple questions are always useful when you start out. These are what variation occurs within the variables, and what co-variation occurs between the variables.

You should use the tidyverse and ggplot2 for these exercises.

library(tidyverse)

Exercise 1:

We are interested in highway miles per gallon, or the hwy variable. Create a histogram of this variable. Describe what you see/learn.

ggplot(mpg, aes(hwy)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 2) + labs(caption = " ")

The histogram seem to be bi modal with two spikes, one spike between 10-20 and another between 20-30.

Exercise 2:

Create a scatterplot. Put hwy on the x-axis and cty on the y-axis. Describe what you notice. Is there a relationship between hwy and cty? What does this mean?

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy , y = cty)) +
  geom_point()

Highway miles per gallon (hwy) and city miles per gallon (cty) seem to be positively correlated. The miles per gallon increase with more miles which makes sense as drivers use highways with higher mile and cities for lower miles.

Exercise 3:

Make a bar plot of manufacturer. Flip it so that the manufacturers are on the y-axis. Order the bars by height. Which manufacturer produced the most cars? Which produced the least?

ggplot(mpg, aes(x=reorder(manufacturer, manufacturer, function(x)-length(x))))+
  coord_flip()+
  geom_bar(aes(stat = "bin"))

Dodge produced the most Lincoln produced the least

Exercise 4:

Make a box plot of hwy, grouped by cyl. Do you see a pattern? If so, what?

ggplot(mpg, aes(cyl,hwy, fill=cyl)) +geom_boxplot()

On highway, average cyl is 6

Exercise 5:

Use the corrplot package to make a lower triangle correlation matrix of the mpg dataset. (Hint: You can find information on the package here.)

Which variables are positively or negatively correlated with which others? Do these relationships make sense to you? Are there any that surprise you?

library(corrplot)
new_mpg<-select(mpg,displ,cyl,cty, hwy)
M <-cor(new_mpg)
corrplot(M, method="circle", type = "lower")

The variables that are positively correlated are hwy & hwy,cty & hwy, cty& cty

The variables that are negatively correlated displ & displ, cyl & displ, cty &displ, hwy & displ, cyl & hwy

Exercise 6:

Recreate the following graphic, as closely as you can. Hint: Use the ggthemes package.

ggplot(mpg, aes(hwy,class)) +
  geom_boxplot() + 
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.2)+ 
  theme_minimal() + 
  theme (
    axis.title.x = element_text(size = 12),
    axis.title.y = element_text(size = 12),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 12),
  axis.line.x = element_line(size =0.5),
plot.background = element_rect(size = 0.5))+
  labs(x=" Highway MPG", y= "Vehicle Class")
